<section class="lab-section">

<h2>The Science of Cooking Pasta</h2>

<p>
Perfect macaroni begins with understanding how pasta cooks. Pasta is primarily
made from durum wheat semolina, which contains starch and protein. When pasta
is placed in boiling water, several chemical changes occur.
</p>

<h3>Starch Gelatinization</h3>

<p>
As pasta heats in boiling water, the starch granules inside the pasta absorb
water and swell. This process is called <b>gelatinization</b>. The starch
softens and becomes tender, giving pasta its familiar texture.
</p>

<h3>Protein Structure</h3>

<p>
Durum wheat proteins form gluten networks that hold the pasta together while
it cooks. These protein structures prevent the pasta from dissolving in water
while allowing it to soften.
</p>

<h3>Why Salt Matters</h3>

<p>
Salt increases the boiling point of water slightly and seasons the pasta from
within. Professional chefs often say pasta water should taste like the sea.
</p>

</section>


<section class="lab-section alt">

<h2>The Science of Melting Cheese</h2>

<p>
Cheese is a complex mixture of proteins, fat, minerals, and water.
The key protein responsible for cheese structure is <b>casein</b>.
</p>

<h3>Casein Protein Networks</h3>

<p>
In solid cheese, casein proteins form a network that traps fat and moisture.
When cheese is heated, this protein structure loosens, allowing the fats to
flow and the cheese to melt.
</p>

<h3>Why Some Cheeses Melt Better</h3>

<p>
Cheeses that melt smoothly typically have higher moisture and balanced fat
content. Hard aged cheeses often separate into oil and clumps when heated
because their protein networks are too tight.
</p>

<h3>The Role of Emulsification</h3>

<p>
Many mac and cheese recipes use ingredients like milk, butter, or sodium
citrate to stabilize the cheese sauce. These ingredients act as emulsifiers,
helping fat and water stay blended into a smooth sauce.
</p>

</section>


